issue.title: k8s_cp state=from_pod requires 'find' binary to be present on the remote pod

labels.name: type/bug
labels.description: Something isn't working

issue.body:
<!--- Verify first that your issue is not already reported on GitHub -->
<!--- Also test if the latest release and devel branch are affected too -->
<!--- Complete *all* sections as described, this form is processed automatically -->

##### SUMMARY
Using the k8s_cp module with state=from_pod requires the `find` command to be present on the remote pod. With newer base docker images like openjdk:17 there is no find command on them. This requirement is also not stated in the documentation.

The code in `plugins/module_utils/copy.py` uses `find` to list files if the remote path is a folder. However this is not needed if it is a file and not a folder. 

There should be a better way to list the files in a folder without relying on OS binaries. Or there could be an argument like `isDir: true` if the file being copied is a folder or not.

commits.message:
Make context managers better

This commit introduces a new ContextManager decorator that builds on top
of contextlib.contextmanager and effectively makes context managers
a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same
as the outermost context of that particular kind.
This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally
use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix
and nest context managers almost freely.
There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example
macro_definitions() and sections(), that, when combined, will overwrite
each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.

Signed-off-by: Nikola Forró <nforro@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #153 from packit/context_management

Make context managers better

This commit introduces a new ContextManager decorator that builds on top of contextlib.contextmanager and effectively makes context managers a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same as the outermost context of that particular kind.
This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix and nest context managers almost freely.
There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example macro_definitions() and sections(), that, when combined, will overwrite each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.
Now it is also possible to access data directly, avoiding the with statement, by using GeneratorContextManager.content property (I'm open to suggestions how to name it better):
for tag in spec.tags().content:
    print(f"{tag.name}: {tag.expanded_value}")
No modifications will be preserved though.

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN
Context managers (Specfile.sections(), Specfile.tags() etc.) can now be nested and combined together (with one exception - Specfile.macro_definitions()), and it is also possible to use tag properties (e.g. Specfile.version, Specfile.license) inside them. It is also possible to access the data directly, avoiding the with statement, by using the content property (e.g. Specfile.tags().content), but be aware that no modifications done to such data will be preserved. You must use with to make changes.
RELEASE NOTES END

Reviewed-by: František Nečas <frantisek.necas@protonmail.com>
Reviewed-by: Nikola Forró <None>

pull_request.title: Make context managers better
pull_request.body:
This commit introduces a new `ContextManager` decorator that builds on top of `contextlib.contextmanager` and effectively makes context managers a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same as the outermost context of that particular kind.

This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix and nest context managers almost freely.

There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example `macro_definitions()` and `sections()`, that, when combined, will overwrite each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.

Now it is also possible to access data directly, avoiding the `with` statement, by using `GeneratorContextManager.content` property (I'm open to suggestions how to name it better):

```python
for tag in spec.tags().content:
    print(f"{tag.name}: {tag.expanded_value}")
```

No modifications will be preserved though.

---

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN

Context managers (`Specfile.sections()`, `Specfile.tags()` etc.) can now be nested and combined together (with one exception - `Specfile.macro_definitions()`), and it is also possible to use tag properties (e.g. `Specfile.version`, `Specfile.license`) inside them. It is also possible to access the data directly, avoiding the `with` statement, by using the `content` property (e.g. `Specfile.tags().content`), but be aware that no modifications done to such data will be preserved. You must use `with` to make changes.

RELEASE NOTES END

issue.body:
##### SUMMARY
<!--- Describe the change below, including rationale and design decisions -->
Add support for private vlans configuration to ios_vlans. Fixes ansible-collections/cisco.ios#693
<!--- HINT: Include "Fixes #nnn" if you are fixing an existing issue -->

##### ISSUE TYPE
<!--- Pick one below and delete the rest -->
- Feature Pull Request

##### COMPONENT NAME
<!--- Write the short name of the module, plugin, task or feature below -->
`ios_vlans`

##### ADDITIONAL INFORMATION
This is my first contribution to Ansible. I've written and tested my changes successfully, but these are items I'm still uncertain about at time of writing:
- I was not able to figure out how to run integration tests. I wrote 1 integration test, but was not able to write a more complete test because I couldn't figure out how to run it myself
- I'm not certain if the unit tests I wrote are thorough enough, feedback would be appreciated

commits.message:
change(celery): retry backoff 3 → 7

This also changes retry setup for creation of bodhi updates to 5.
All other tasks are still on 2.

When will the retrying happen?

  0-7s, 0-14s, 0-28s, 0-48s, 0-96s

We have jitter on (celery's default) so it's actual `random(0, value)`.

This is done mainly to account for koji build tagging as it can take
tenths of seconds easily. We also wanted to increase the backoff since
it makes more sense to retry later: the initial condition may not be
resolved right away.

Brutally related #1615

Signed-off-by: Tomas Tomecek <ttomecek@redhat.com>
Co-authored-by: Laura Barcziova <lbarcziova@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #1800 from TomasTomecek/related-1615

change(celery): retry backoff 3 → 7

This also changes retry setup for creation of bodhi updates to 5.
All other tasks are still on 2.
When will the retrying happen?
0-7s, 0-14s, 0-28s, 0-48s, 0-96s

We have jitter on (celery's default) so it's actual random(0, value).
This is done mainly to account for koji build tagging as it can take
tenths of seconds easily. We also wanted to increase the backoff since
it makes more sense to retry later: the initial condition may not be
resolved right away.
Brutally related #1615
// meant to be a oneliner

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN
We've increased internal task retry backoff time in Packit GitHub app from 3 to 7 seconds. We hope this will increase success for network flakes and random infrastructure issues. Creation of bodhi updates should be now more reliable too as Packit will try more times (from 2 to 5).
RELEASE NOTES END

Reviewed-by: Laura Barcziová <None>
Reviewed-by: Tomas Tomecek <tomas@tomecek.net>

issue.title: Make toolbox list behave in the same way podman images does

milestone.title: Release 0.1.0
milestone.description: Toolbox has been rewritten, now we need to catch all the remaining bugs and tweak things here and there and release v0.1.0.

issue.body:
This PR should fix #1043.

It makes `toolbox list` behave in the same way as `podman images`
```
[test@fedora build]$ podman images 
REPOSITORY                                                       TAG         IMAGE ID      CREATED      SIZE
registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/toolbox                          latest      c24104d7b237  2 weeks ago  596 MB
<INTERNAL_URL>/toolbox-container                             9.0.0-9     c24104d7b237  2 weeks ago  596 MB
[test@fedora build]$ toolbox list 
IMAGE ID      IMAGE NAME                                                               CREATED
c24104d7b237  registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/toolbox:latest                           2 weeks ago
c24104d7b237  <INTERNAL_URL>/toolbox-container:9.0.0-9                            2 weeks ago
```

As mentioned in the issue `podman images --format json` returns image twice with multiple `Names`, so my approach is to detect images with the same ID (this comes from the assumption that those image record are really identical), then print image twice with both names.

issue.body:
Real world example:
```python
%{?el9:Patch1:  001-requests-chardet-unbundled.patch}
```

commits.message:
Handle tags in conditional macro expansions

Take advantage of `ValueParser`, since it's a more robust solution than
using regexes. Use the same approach also for `%prep` macros.

Signed-off-by: Nikola Forró <nforro@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #156 from packit/conditional_macro_expansions

Handle tags in conditional macro expansions

Take advantage of ValueParser, since it's a more robust solution than using regexes. Use the same approach also for %prep macros.
Fixes #151.
RELEASE NOTES BEGIN
Tags enclosed in conditional macro expansions are not ignored anymore.
RELEASE NOTES END

Reviewed-by: Jiri Popelka <None>

issue.title: k8s_cp state=from_pod requires 'find' binary to be present on the remote pod

labels.name: type/bug
labels.description: Something isn't working

issue.body:
<!--- Verify first that your issue is not already reported on GitHub -->
<!--- Also test if the latest release and devel branch are affected too -->
<!--- Complete *all* sections as described, this form is processed automatically -->

##### SUMMARY
Using the k8s_cp module with state=from_pod requires the `find` command to be present on the remote pod. With newer base docker images like openjdk:17 there is no find command on them. This requirement is also not stated in the documentation.

The code in `plugins/module_utils/copy.py` uses `find` to list files if the remote path is a folder. However this is not needed if it is a file and not a folder. 

There should be a better way to list the files in a folder without relying on OS binaries. Or there could be an argument like `isDir: true` if the file being copied is a folder or not.

commits.message:
Make context managers better

This commit introduces a new ContextManager decorator that builds on top
of contextlib.contextmanager and effectively makes context managers
a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same
as the outermost context of that particular kind.
This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally
use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix
and nest context managers almost freely.
There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example
macro_definitions() and sections(), that, when combined, will overwrite
each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.

Signed-off-by: Nikola Forró <nforro@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #153 from packit/context_management

Make context managers better

This commit introduces a new ContextManager decorator that builds on top of contextlib.contextmanager and effectively makes context managers a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same as the outermost context of that particular kind.
This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix and nest context managers almost freely.
There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example macro_definitions() and sections(), that, when combined, will overwrite each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.
Now it is also possible to access data directly, avoiding the with statement, by using GeneratorContextManager.content property (I'm open to suggestions how to name it better):
for tag in spec.tags().content:
    print(f"{tag.name}: {tag.expanded_value}")
No modifications will be preserved though.

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN
Context managers (Specfile.sections(), Specfile.tags() etc.) can now be nested and combined together (with one exception - Specfile.macro_definitions()), and it is also possible to use tag properties (e.g. Specfile.version, Specfile.license) inside them. It is also possible to access the data directly, avoiding the with statement, by using the content property (e.g. Specfile.tags().content), but be aware that no modifications done to such data will be preserved. You must use with to make changes.
RELEASE NOTES END

Reviewed-by: František Nečas <frantisek.necas@protonmail.com>
Reviewed-by: Nikola Forró <None>

pull_request.title: Make context managers better
pull_request.body:
This commit introduces a new `ContextManager` decorator that builds on top of `contextlib.contextmanager` and effectively makes context managers a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same as the outermost context of that particular kind.

This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix and nest context managers almost freely.

There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example `macro_definitions()` and `sections()`, that, when combined, will overwrite each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.

Now it is also possible to access data directly, avoiding the `with` statement, by using `GeneratorContextManager.content` property (I'm open to suggestions how to name it better):

```python
for tag in spec.tags().content:
    print(f"{tag.name}: {tag.expanded_value}")
```

No modifications will be preserved though.

---

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN

Context managers (`Specfile.sections()`, `Specfile.tags()` etc.) can now be nested and combined together (with one exception - `Specfile.macro_definitions()`), and it is also possible to use tag properties (e.g. `Specfile.version`, `Specfile.license`) inside them. It is also possible to access the data directly, avoiding the `with` statement, by using the `content` property (e.g. `Specfile.tags().content`), but be aware that no modifications done to such data will be preserved. You must use `with` to make changes.

RELEASE NOTES END

commits.message:
change(celery): retry backoff 3 → 7

This also changes retry setup for creation of bodhi updates to 5.
All other tasks are still on 2.

When will the retrying happen?

  0-7s, 0-14s, 0-28s, 0-48s, 0-96s

We have jitter on (celery's default) so it's actual `random(0, value)`.

This is done mainly to account for koji build tagging as it can take
tenths of seconds easily. We also wanted to increase the backoff since
it makes more sense to retry later: the initial condition may not be
resolved right away.

Brutally related #1615

Signed-off-by: Tomas Tomecek <ttomecek@redhat.com>
Co-authored-by: Laura Barcziova <lbarcziova@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #1800 from TomasTomecek/related-1615

change(celery): retry backoff 3 → 7

This also changes retry setup for creation of bodhi updates to 5.
All other tasks are still on 2.
When will the retrying happen?
0-7s, 0-14s, 0-28s, 0-48s, 0-96s

We have jitter on (celery's default) so it's actual random(0, value).
This is done mainly to account for koji build tagging as it can take
tenths of seconds easily. We also wanted to increase the backoff since
it makes more sense to retry later: the initial condition may not be
resolved right away.
Brutally related #1615
// meant to be a oneliner

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN
We've increased internal task retry backoff time in Packit GitHub app from 3 to 7 seconds. We hope this will increase success for network flakes and random infrastructure issues. Creation of bodhi updates should be now more reliable too as Packit will try more times (from 2 to 5).
RELEASE NOTES END

issue.title: Make toolbox list behave in the same way podman images does

milestone.title: Release 0.1.0
milestone.description: Toolbox has been rewritten, now we need to catch all the remaining bugs and tweak things here and there and release v0.1.0.

issue.body:
This PR should fix #1043.

It makes `toolbox list` behave in the same way as `podman images`
```
[test@fedora build]$ podman images 
REPOSITORY                                                       TAG         IMAGE ID      CREATED      SIZE
registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/toolbox                          latest      c24104d7b237  2 weeks ago  596 MB
<INTERNAL_URL>/toolbox-container                             9.0.0-9     c24104d7b237  2 weeks ago  596 MB
[test@fedora build]$ toolbox list 
IMAGE ID      IMAGE NAME                                                               CREATED
c24104d7b237  registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/toolbox:latest                           2 weeks ago
c24104d7b237  <INTERNAL_URL>/toolbox-container:9.0.0-9                            2 weeks ago
```

As mentioned in the issue `podman images --format json` returns image twice with multiple `Names`, so my approach is to detect images with the same ID (this comes from the assumption that those image record are really identical), then print image twice with both names.

Handle tags in conditional macro expansions

Take advantage of `ValueParser`, since it's a more robust solution than
using regexes. Use the same approach also for `%prep` macros.

Signed-off-by: Nikola Forró <nforro@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #156 from packit/conditional_macro_expansions

Handle tags in conditional macro expansions

Take advantage of ValueParser, since it's a more robust solution than using regexes. Use the same approach also for %prep macros.
Fixes #151.

Tags enclosed in conditional macro expansions are not ignored anymore.
RELEASE NOTES END

issue.title: k8s_cp state=from_pod requires 'find' binary to be present on the remote pod

labels.name: type/bug
labels.description: Something isn't working

issue.body:
<!--- Verify first that your issue is not already reported on GitHub -->
<!--- Also test if the latest release and devel branch are affected too -->
<!--- Complete *all* sections as described, this form is processed automatically -->

##### SUMMARY
Using the k8s_cp module with state=from_pod requires the `find` command to be present on the remote pod. With newer base docker images like openjdk:17 there is no find command on them. This requirement is also not stated in the documentation.

The code in `plugins/module_utils/copy.py` uses `find` to list files if the remote path is a folder. However this is not needed if it is a file and not a folder. 

There should be a better way to list the files in a folder without relying on OS binaries. Or there could be an argument like `isDir: true` if the file being copied is a folder or not.

issue.title: k8s_cp doc issue

labels.name: type/documentation
labels.description: Improvements or additions to documentation

labels.name: good first issue
labels.description: Good for newcomers

labels.name: waiting_on_contributor
labels.description: Needs help. Feel free to engage to get things unblocked

issue.body:
<!--- Verify first that your improvement is not already reported on GitHub -->
<!--- Also test if the latest release and devel branch are affected too -->
<!--- Complete *all* sections as described, this form is processed automatically -->

##### SUMMARY
<!--- Explain the problem briefly below, add suggestions to wording or structure -->
Last example for the k8s_cp is with typo

```
# copy content into a file in the remote pod
- name: Copy /tmp/foo from a remote pod to /tmp/bar locally
  kubernetes.core.k8s_cp:
    state: to_pod
    namespace: some-namespace
    pod: some-pod
    remote_path: /tmp/foo.txt
    content: "This content will be copied into remote file"

issue.title: k8s_cp state=from_pod requires 'find' binary to be present on the remote pod

labels.name: type/bug
labels.description: Something isn't working

issue.body:
<!--- Verify first that your issue is not already reported on GitHub -->
<!--- Also test if the latest release and devel branch are affected too -->
<!--- Complete *all* sections as described, this form is processed automatically -->

##### SUMMARY
Using the k8s_cp module with state=from_pod requires the `find` command to be present on the remote pod. With newer base docker images like openjdk:17 there is no find command on them. This requirement is also not stated in the documentation.

The code in `plugins/module_utils/copy.py` uses `find` to list files if the remote path is a folder. However this is not needed if it is a file and not a folder. 

There should be a better way to list the files in a folder without relying on OS binaries. Or there could be an argument like `isDir: true` if the file being copied is a folder or not.

commits.message:
Make context managers better

This commit introduces a new ContextManager decorator that builds on top
of contextlib.contextmanager and effectively makes context managers
a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same
as the outermost context of that particular kind.
This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally
use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix
and nest context managers almost freely.
There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example
macro_definitions() and sections(), that, when combined, will overwrite
each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.

Signed-off-by: Nikola Forró <nforro@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #153 from packit/context_management

Make context managers better

This commit introduces a new ContextManager decorator that builds on top of contextlib.contextmanager and effectively makes context managers a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same as the outermost context of that particular kind.
This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix and nest context managers almost freely.
There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example macro_definitions() and sections(), that, when combined, will overwrite each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.
Now it is also possible to access data directly, avoiding the with statement, by using GeneratorContextManager.content property (I'm open to suggestions how to name it better):
for tag in spec.tags().content:
    print(f"{tag.name}: {tag.expanded_value}")
No modifications will be preserved though.

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN
Context managers (Specfile.sections(), Specfile.tags() etc.) can now be nested and combined together (with one exception - Specfile.macro_definitions()), and it is also possible to use tag properties (e.g. Specfile.version, Specfile.license) inside them. It is also possible to access the data directly, avoiding the with statement, by using the content property (e.g. Specfile.tags().content), but be aware that no modifications done to such data will be preserved. You must use with to make changes.
RELEASE NOTES END

Reviewed-by: František Nečas <frantisek.necas@protonmail.com>
Reviewed-by: Nikola Forró <None>

pull_request.title: Make context managers better
pull_request.body:
This commit introduces a new `ContextManager` decorator that builds on top of `contextlib.contextmanager` and effectively makes context managers a singleton. Any nested context of the same kind will be the same as the outermost context of that particular kind.

This makes it possible, for example, to set properties that internally use context managers inside an existing context, or in general mix and nest context managers almost freely.

There are still instances of conflicting context managers, for example `macro_definitions()` and `sections()`, that, when combined, will overwrite each other's underlying data. All such instances will be documented.

Now it is also possible to access data directly, avoiding the `with` statement, by using `GeneratorContextManager.content` property (I'm open to suggestions how to name it better):

```python
for tag in spec.tags().content:
    print(f"{tag.name}: {tag.expanded_value}")
```

No modifications will be preserved though.

---

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN

Context managers (`Specfile.sections()`, `Specfile.tags()` etc.) can now be nested and combined together (with one exception - `Specfile.macro_definitions()`), and it is also possible to use tag properties (e.g. `Specfile.version`, `Specfile.license`) inside them. It is also possible to access the data directly, avoiding the `with` statement, by using the `content` property (e.g. `Specfile.tags().content`), but be aware that no modifications done to such data will be preserved. You must use `with` to make changes.

RELEASE NOTES END

##### SUMMARY

Add support for private vlans configuration to ios_vlans. Fixes ansible-collections/cisco.ios#693
<!--- HINT: Include "Fixes #nnn" if you are fixing an existing issue -->

##### ISSUE TYPE
<!--- Pick one below and delete the rest -->
- Feature Pull Request

`ios_vlans`

##### ADDITIONAL INFORMATION
This is my first contribution to Ansible. I've written and tested my changes successfully, but these are items I'm still uncertain about at time of writing:
- I was not able to figure out how to run integration tests. I wrote 1 integration test, but was not able to write a more complete test because I couldn't figure out how to run it myself
- I'm not certain if the unit tests I wrote are thorough enough, feedback would be appreciated

commits.message:
change(celery): retry backoff 3 → 7

This also changes retry setup for creation of bodhi updates to 5.
All other tasks are still on 2.

When will the retrying happen?

  0-7s, 0-14s, 0-28s, 0-48s, 0-96s

We have jitter on (celery's default) so it's actual `random(0, value)`.

This is done mainly to account for koji build tagging as it can take
tenths of seconds easily. We also wanted to increase the backoff since
it makes more sense to retry later: the initial condition may not be
resolved right away.

Brutally related #1615

Signed-off-by: Tomas Tomecek <ttomecek@redhat.com>
Co-authored-by: Laura Barcziova <lbarcziova@redhat.com>

Merge pull request #1800 from TomasTomecek/related-1615

change(celery): retry backoff 3 → 7

This also changes retry setup for creation of bodhi updates to 5.
All other tasks are still on 2.
When will the retrying happen?
0-7s, 0-14s, 0-28s, 0-48s, 0-96s

We have jitter on (celery's default) so it's actual random(0, value).
This is done mainly to account for koji build tagging as it can take
tenths of seconds easily. We also wanted to increase the backoff since
it makes more sense to retry later: the initial condition may not be
resolved right away.
Brutally related #1615
// meant to be a oneliner

RELEASE NOTES BEGIN
We've increased internal task retry backoff time in Packit GitHub app from 3 to 7 seconds. We hope this will increase success for network flakes and random infrastructure issues. Creation of bodhi updates should be now more reliable too as Packit will try more times (from 2 to 5).
RELEASE NOTES END

Reviewed-by: Laura Barcziová <None>

issue.title: Make toolbox list behave in the same way podman images does

milestone.title: Release 0.1.0
milestone.description: Toolbox has been rewritten, now we need to catch all the remaining bugs and tweak things here and there and release v0.1.0.

issue.body:
This PR should fix #1043.

It makes `toolbox list` behave in the same way as `podman images`
```
[test@fedora build]$ podman images 
REPOSITORY                                                       TAG         IMAGE ID      CREATED      SIZE
registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/toolbox                          latest      c24104d7b237  2 weeks ago  596 MB
<INTERNAL_URL>/toolbox-container                             9.0.0-9     c24104d7b237  2 weeks ago  596 MB
[test@fedora build]$ toolbox list 
IMAGE ID      IMAGE NAME                                                               CREATED
c24104d7b237  registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9/toolbox:latest                           2 weeks ago
c24104d7b237  <INTERNAL_URL>/toolbox-container:9.0.0-9                            2 weeks ago
```

As mentioned in the issue `podman images --format json` returns image twice with multiple `Names`, so my approach is to detect images with the same ID (this comes from the assumption that those image record are really identical), then print image twice with both names.
